https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=48AOOynnmqU Goes into some depth. The tl;dw is, there are two separate but converging forces at work. One is that marketing firms now hire people to create bots for them that make phony web pages full of text generated by a PERL script to bump their clients' product's search results up one slot in a Google search. This buries real information under a mountain of garbage. The other is that the people who own Twitter, Facebook, Reddit, etc., make it harder every year to see any information in them from the outside, in order to force you to install their software on your phone and give them all your yummy, yummy personal information, so that they can sell it to marketing firms. They are working very hard to make the information in their forums, discussion groups, the sort of information that even five years ago you could have found by googling and seeing information scraped from phpBB forums, is all being locked away in the "walled gardens" of proprietary Internet forums.

And the tl;dr of that is, advertisers and marketers are why we can't have nice things. They destroyed Usenet, they are in the process of destroying email, and they're destroying the dubya-dubya-dubya as a usable source of information about anything whatsoever other than buying cheap plastic Chinese trash on Amazon.

Not to mention the increased regulation vastly favors large corporations over individual users, because individual users have next to no lobbying power. In that it mirrors shit we've seen in real life. For example, increased regulation gets pushed through under soft sounding, left-leaning arguments of better worker rights, but now Joe the grocer with his two employees has to abide by the same morass of rules that corporations have entire legal departments for. The internet used to be replete with resources ran by individuals or small groups, and they have increasingly disappeared to make way for large groups, or those individuals being bound to corporate aggregator sites. Sites which are, indeed, involved in constantly exercising more and more control over their visitors and their creative stables. Even the way out for many is something controlled by another large corporation: Patreon. Compare that to the rise of the consumer internet where, if you wanted to buy a product or support a creator, you went directly to the bank without a middle man.
